HEADWORD: Threshold
<hw>Thresh"old</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>threswold</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧reshwold</ets>, AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧rescwald</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧erscwald</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧erscold</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧rescold</ets>, fr.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧rescan</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧erscan</ets>, to thresh; akin to
Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧reskj⟦oum⟧de</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦oum⟧skuldr</ets>,
Sw. <ets>tr⟦oum⟧skel</ets>, Dan. <ets>t⟦ae⟧rskel</ets>. See
<er>Thrash</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The plank, stone, or piece of
timber, which lies under a door, especially of a dwelling house, church,
temple, or the like; the doorsill; hence, entrance; gate;
door.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: The place or point of entering or beginning,
entrance; outset; <as>as, the <ex>threshold</ex> of life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Threshwold</ent>⟦br⟧
